{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657402/1923101301/0049.xml":{"full_text":"3.452.5G6 AUTOS\nGO TOSCRAP HEAP\nReplacing of Machines Made\nin 1916 and 1917 Great\nBoon to Manufacturers.\nBY J. C. RWYLE,\nFpaclal Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK. October 13. \u2014Who is\nbuying\u2019 the tremendous number of\nautomobiles being built this year, and\nwho will buy the more than four mil\nlion cars which will be built in 1924?\nThe answer to that question rests\nlargely on replacement needs. More\nthan two million present owners of\nautomobiles and trucks will be num\nbered among the purchasers in the\nnext twelve months. For the replace\nment requirements of the United States\nnow are more than two million cars a\nyear. This business alone, with the\ncollateral demand for parts, is sufficient\nto keep the automotive industry mov\ning at a fair pace the year round.\nMillions of Autos Scrapped.\nManufacturers are not going to be\ncontent with a fair pace, however.\nProduction schedules the remainder of\nthis year and a large part of next give\npromise of being heavier than ever be\nfore. Price cuts by many manufac\nturers will necessitate the proportion\nate cutting of overhead per car, which\ncan only be assured by quantity produc\ntion. As a result it is estimated that\nemployment in the industry will be one\nthird greater than last year, through\nout the winter.\nThe tremendous dumber of vehicles\nwhich will be thrown on the market\nis not viewed with great alarm by\nmost manufacturers as they realize\nthat practically all the 1,583.617 cars\nmade In 1916 and the 1,868,949 cars\nturned out in 1917 are now on the\nscrap heap.\nbower Prices Seen Ahead.\nSince the cut In Ford prices, senti\nment in the trade has settled down\nand no startling developments are ex\npected until the New York automobile\nshow, in January. Some makers are\nplanning fireworks for that occasion,\nwhich will evoke a long drawn \u201dah\na-a-a\u201d from the public. One maker\npromises an Innovation in equipment,\nwhich, he says, will be the biggest\nsensation in ten years Another well\nknown maker is expected to announce\nnew low prices in connection with\nnew models, which will shock the in\ndustry.\nIn the meantime, sales throughout\nthe country are holding up unusually\nwell, according to factory reports\nfrom dealers.\nEnormous Output Planned.\nPreliminary schedules of produc\ntion for the Ford Company for No\nvember and December Indicate an\noutturn of 1,900,000 for the current\nyear.\nThe remaining 112 leading makers\nare expected to turn out an equal num\nber which will bring the year's total to\nabout 3,800.000 vehicles. The Ford\nCompany turned out its eight million\nfive hundred thousandth motor October\n4. This shows a production of 500,000\ncars in seven days less than three\nmonths. Even if this rate were not ex\nceeded, the nine millionth motor should\nbe made about January 1 and the ten\nmillionth about July of next year. Sales\nof Ford cars and trucks in September\ntotaled 141,467, an increase of over\n35,000, as compared with September,\n1922.\nAutomobile Makers Buy Copper,\nAutomobile manufacturers are taking\nfull advantage of the present low price\nof copper to buy the red metal and cop\nper products in anticipation of their\nneeds. In other lines the demand has\nshown a falling off, due in some meas\nure to the usual seasonal decline. A\nshort time ago there was a movement\non foot to send copper to German fab\nricators without title to the meta! pass\ning out of the hands of shippers. Under\nthis plan, the German manufacturers\nwere to turn it into manufactured goods\nwhich would be sent back to the ship\npers In this country who would market\nthem and remit to the fabricators the\ncost of manufacture with a profit added.\nThe recent disorganized condition of\nGerman industry, the almost complete\nloss of value of the mark as a medium\nof exchange and the growing belief\nthat German copper consumers have\nample funds in pounds and dollars to\nfinance copper purchases without such\naid has resulted in the dropping of this\nplan, at least temporarily.\nFURTHER DECLINE\nFORCED IN STOCKS\nCoppers, Steels, Bails and Oils Go\nlower in Week\u2019s\nTrading.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, October 13.\u2014Specula\ntive forces working for the decline\nmade further progress in this week\u2019s\nstock market, although the so-called J\npivotal industrial stocks offered stub-\nborn resistance to selling pressure 1\naround their previous lows.\nThere were a few constructive news\ndevelopments during the week such\nas the declaration of the Sinclair divi\ndend. previously reported in danger;\na new high record in railroad car\nloadings; reports of larger inquiries\nfor steel from railroad sources and\nthe usual optimistic statements on the\neconomic situation by banking and\nbusiness leaders, but the stock market j\npaid little or no attention to them, i\nCopper shares were sharply depress\ned, Anaconda and some of the minor\nIssues falling to new low records for\nthe year. Rubbers also lost ground.\nThe continued shrinkage in the un-\nfilled orders of the United States Steel\nCorporation and lessened production\nhad a depressing effect on the steel\nshares. Motors and motor accessories\nwitnessed the usual seasonal Uquida-\ntlon.\nThe oils showed more stability, and\nsugars developed Intervals of strength\non reports of higher commodity prices.\nRailroad shares were unable to\nmaintain the rally which set in iate\nlast week, operations for the advance\nbeing suspended when it was dis\ncovered that they were attracting\nlittle outside participation.\nGermany\u2019s currency continued its i\ndownward course. French francs\nshowed marked improvement.\nGASOLINE 7 CENTS I\nA GALLON IN TEXAS\nPrice War in San Antonio Big\nHelp to Owners of Au\ntomobiles.\nBy the Associated Press.\nSAN ANTONIO. Tex.. October 13.\nGasoline was retailing in many filling\nstations here today at 7 cents a gal\nlon. The price was believed to be\nthe lowest In the United States.\nThe Atlas Petroleum Company,\nwhich operates a refinery here, an\nnounced that because prices had been\nmanipulated without regard to cost\nit would maintain the price at 7 cents\nuntil the market became stabilized,\nalthough no profit was made.\nThe Gulf company reduced its price\nfrom 13 to 11 certs Wednesday and\nwas followed by other major com\npanies Thursday.\n\nFINANCIAL\u2019.\nNEW YORK CURB MARKET 1\nReceived by Private Wire Direct to The Star Office\nBY 'WILLIAM F. HEFFERN\u2019AN.\nNEW YORK. October 13.\u2014Interest\nin the curb market today was divided\nbetween Durant Motors and the oil\nshares. Durant had sold as low as 23\non Thursday, which was its absolute\nlow record. It had closed at 25%.\nOn fairly active trading it Jumped up\nduring the two hours today over five\npoints.\nDurant has long earned the right\nto be classed as a mystery stock. The\nway it was handled in the beginning\nhas been a matter of common criti\ncism. Whether or not much stock\nwas sold to the public around the\nhigh prices is not known. But the\nimpression is that a good many peo\nple were Induced to buy on reports of\nthe extraordinary success which the\nDurant cars were having.\nNEW YORK, October 13.\u2014Following\nis an official list of bonds and stocks\ntraded in on the New York Curb Mar\nket today;\nSales In BONDS,\nthousands High. Low. Close.\nJ Allied Packer* Bs.. 67% 67% 67%\n4 Alum 7\u00ab \u201925 102% 102% 10\u00b0%\n22 Alum 7s new \u201933.. 10(1% 100% 106%\nr# Am Cot OH Oh 99 99 jin\u2019*\nlAm Gas Elec \u00abs.. 94% 94% 94%\n1 Am Light 6k 103% 103% 103%\nlAm Suniat Tob 7%s 96% 9(1% 96%\n6Am T T6s \u201924.. 100% 100% 100%\n3 Anaconda 6s 101% 101% 101%\n2 Anglo Am OH 7%s 102 102 102\nBArACo of Del 5%s 89% 89% 89%\n6AtO*W ISS 8s 46% 46% 40%\n7 Beth Steel 7s '35.. 103 102% 102%\n1? <>nt Steel 8s 107% 107% J 07%\n1 Charcoal Co Am 8s 90 90 90\n5Si 1 p 5 V45.. 08% 08% 08%\n2 Cit Sere 7s C 88% 88% 88%\n1.1 Clt Scrv 7s I) 88% 88 88\n1 Col Or 8s part cfs 18% 18% 18%\n3 (\u2019on Gas Balt 6s A 101% 101% 101%\n3 Cons Textiles 8s 9494% 94%\n1 Cuban Tel 7%5.... 10.1 \u2019or.\u2019 10.1\n16 Kn fit Ter 5%a w i 99% 99% 99%\n1 Kennecott Cop 75.. 103% 103% 103%\n8 Libby McN A Lib 7e 99% 99% 99%\n6 Llg Win Llg r e 7s 102% 102% 102%\n1 Manitoba Pow 7s W 100 100 100\n4 Morris A Co 7%5.. 100% 100 100%\n1 New Or Pub Scrv 5s 84 84 84\n1 Ohio Power 5s 8.. 85 8.1 85\n2 Penn Pow A Lt .Is 86 86 86\n10 Pub Servos N J 7s 100% 100% 100%\n13 Pub Serv El Pow 6s 96 9.1% 9.1%\n1 S O N Y 7s '2B 104 104 104'\nISON Y 6%b 106 106 106\n3 Swift ACo os 91% 91% 91%\n5Un Oil 6s B '25 99% 99% 99%\n1 Vacuum Oil 7s 106 106 106\nFOREIGN BONDS.\n4 Ovt of Argen 6s w 1 993; 99% 99%\n2 King of Nether 6s. 98 98 98\n11 Swiss Govt 6%s 99% 99% 99%\n2 Swiss Govt 5s 97% 97% 97%\nSales STANDARD OIL ISSUES,\nin units.\n120 Buckeye P L 77% 76% 76%\n10 Cumberland P L.. 104 104 104\n30 111 P L 1,17 157 157\n80 Ind P L 96 89 89%\n100 Inter Pet Co Ltd 1,1% 15% 15%\n100 Nat Transit 22% 22% 22%\n300 Ohio Oil new 5.1 54% 54%\n20 Prairie Oil A Gas 167 167 167\n30 Prairie PL 99 98% 99\n3500 S O Ind 54% 34% 54%\n10 Southern P L 01% 91% 91%\n10 S O Kansas new.. 39% 39% 39%\n100 SO Ky 91% 91 91%\n100 SONY new 41% 41% 41%\n500 Vacuum Oii new.. GO 49% 50\nSales INDEPENDENT OIL STOCKS.\nIn hundreds.\n8 Ark Nat Gag 5% 5% 5%\n5 Carib Synd 3% 3% 3%\n1 Cities Service 130 129 130\n4 Cities Service pfd. 67% 67% 67%\n2 Clt Serv B cfs 13 12% 13\nSI,OOO Cit Serv C scrip. 70 70 70\nSI,OOO Cit Serv scrip 79 79 79\n8 Creole Synd 1% I*l 1%\n1 Derh O A Ref w 15% 5% 5%\n10 Engineers Pet 05 .0.1 .05\n10 Federal Oil 30 .30 .30\n1 Glen Rock Oil 70 .70 .70\n131 Gulf States Oil ..6% 6 6%\n15 Gulf States OAR 1% 1% 1%\n20 Hudson Oil 05 .0.1 .0.1\n110 Keystone Ranger.. .03 .03 .03\n70 Mex Oil 80 .74 .78\n2 Mex Panuco SO .80 .80\nWORLD TRADE NOW\nLOOKING UPWARD\n\nBritain Notes Big Increase in*\nExports\u2014Tourists Lavish\nWith Money Abroad.\n__________\nBy Cable to The Star and Chicago Dally News.\nCopyright, 1923.\nLONDON, October 13.\u2014World trade,\nso long depressed, has entered a new\nand better phase, with every indica\ntion of rapid improvement, according\nto British bankers and economists.\nGreat Britain\u2019s trade figures for Sep\ntember, just published, show a re\nmarkable increase in exports, amount\ning to \u00a33,700,000, over the figures for\nAugust.\nOrders for manufactured products,\nsuch as steel sheets and building ma\nterials, are flooding many industrial\ncenters, especially in the Wales steel\nsection, where the output has been\nsold up to May of next year.\nRapid Trade Expansion.\nThe rapid expansion of trade is re\nsponsible for the recent astonishing\nstatements regarding plans for infla\ntion of the British currency. These\nplans naturally do not contemplate\nany positive inflation of the pound\nsterling, but call for a negative pol\nicy designed to halt deflation, which\nmany authorities hold was carried\nI out far too rapidly,\nj In particular instances, such as the\ni Wales steel industry, the upward\nmovement of trade has been in\nfluenced largely by the Japanese\nearthquake, which caused enormous\ndemands for construction materials.\nOther elements, however, prove that\nthe world's buying power has been\nIncreased generally, regardless of\nlocal Influences.\nSome Degree of Optimism,\nFor the first time since 1921, some\ndegree of optimism prevails in trad\ning circles, replacing the gloomy fore\nbodings occasioned by the French\n.entry into the Ruhr and Europe's fail\nure to settle the outstanding difficul\nties regarding reparations. Some\ndoubt exists as to whether the re-\ncovery of the world would have been\naccelerated if France had-not entered,\nthe Ruhr, but that does not dlmln- i\nish the satisfaction over what recov- i\nery Is now evident. It effectually I\nsrtlences the political prophets who I\nheld that occupation of the Ruhr j\nwould definitely halt trade recovery, i\nMany British industries face an ex\nceedingly hard winter, but apparently\nthe depression of these has been over\ncome by renewed vigor in other lines.\nTourists Flooding Europe. i\ni The desire for travel, unsatisfied!\nj during the long years of the war, j\nI shows no signs of diminishing after\n1 five years of peace, and continues to\nj bring from the countries least as- j\nfected by the war thousands of pros\nperous tourists. Americans in par-\nticular have added vast sums to i\nEurope\u2019s treasuries during the past l\nseason, which began earlier and con- j\ntinued later into the autumn than\neven during the pre-war years. This\nstimulant of international trade is\nrecognized as one of the brightest\nomens.\nWOOL EXPOBTS HEAVY.\nBOSTON, October 13 (Special).\u2014\nThe export movement of raw wool\ncontinues to feature activities in the\nlocal market. Otherwise, this week\nhas been one of the most disap\npointing to the trade for some time.\nWhat domestic demand there was\ncame largely for low grades and\nscoured wools. Quarter-blood fleeces\nsold at 47% cents In the grease and\nthree-eighths bloods at 82 cents.\nWEEKLY BANK REPORT.\nNEW YORK, October 13.\u2014The ac\ntual condition of clearing house\nbanks and trust companies for the\nweek shows an excess in reserve of\n$14,624,210. This is a decrease in re\nserve of $1,336,000,\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C., SATURDAY, OCTOBER 13, 1923.\ni >ii \u2014l,\nj The last few months attempts to\nsupport Durant stock in the markets\nhave been abandoned. It has been\nleft to take care of itself, and the\nunloading even of small blocks has\nbeen attended by severe declines.\nA stock in this position is apt to\nhave an equally abrupt rally and it\nwas one of these rallies which\noccurred today.\nThe curb oils, like those on the\nstock exchange, had evidently got\nover what shock had been occasioned\nby the California price reductions\nearlier in the Week. Also reports\nthat production in the California ter\nritory was on the decrease had a\nsteadying effect. Vacuum oil, Stand\nard of Indiana and ITarle oil were 1\nail firm and fractionally higher. Inde\npendent oils, like Salt Creek, where\nthey were dealt in at all, were some\nwhat higher.\nReading coal rights were in better\ndemand getting ready for their trans\nfer to the stock exchange. Oilleit\nSafety Razor rose a point.\n1 Mount Prod 14% 14% 14%\n1 Mutual Oil vot efta 8% 8% 8%\n5 New Brad Oil w 14% 4% 4%\n2 Peer Oil Corp 85 .83 .8.1\n10 Penn Beaver Oil.. .55 -52 \u2022JJ i\n1 Pennoek Oil 11% I'V4 U%\n2 Roy (\u2019an Oil Ref 8% 3% 3%\n1 Salt Ck Uona 7% 7%\n7 Salt Ck Prod 19 18% 19\n12 Sapnlpa Refln 1% 1%\n5 Seaboard Oil 1% J'l\n10 Sou Stater Oil .15 .15 .15\n3 Turman Oil 6.1 65 65\n22 Wilcox Oil Gas. 4% 4% 4%\n10 Y Oil 0. .07 .0,\nINDUSTRIALS.\n3 Am Cot Fab pfd.. 101 09 101\nI Atlantic Fruit w i 1% 1% 1%\n3 Bklyu Shoe 10% 10 10%\n1 Brit-Am Tob Cou.. 24% 24% 24%\n1 Bklyn City RR 11% 11% U\u201di\n26 Buddy Buda 1% If*\n1 Centrifug Iron Pipe 21 21 -1\n5 Chi Nip new w 1.. 38 38 3S\n_ 1 Colo Pow A Lt pfd 92 92 92\n2 Dubilier C A Radio 10 10 10\n17 Durant Motor 30% 20 30\n5 Durant Mot of Ind 8 7% S\n1 Du Pont Motors 433% 433% 433%\n1 Gillette S R 269 269 269%\n2 Gleasonlte 10% 30% 10%\n3 Hudson Co pfd 16% 16% 16%\n2 Hartman new w i 39% 89% 39%\n2 Int Concrete 10% 10% 10%\n3 Kresge 3.1% 35% 35%\n2 Kresge pfd 31 31 3!\n2 Lehigh Power aec 22% 22 22\n1 N Y Tel Co pfd... 109% 109% 109%\n2 Park A Tilford 25% 2.1% 25%\n1 Radio Corp 2% 2% 2%\n1 Radio Corp pfd... 3c, 3j\u2019\u00ab 3,\u2019*\n28 Read Coal rts w i 22% 22 22%\n1 Reading Coal w 48% 48% 48%\n10 So C A I new .10 .10 .10\n1 Stud Wnlff Rub Co 53% 53% 53%\n1 Swift Int 19 19 19\n3 Tob Prod Export*. 4 3% 3%\n3Un Pft Shar new.. 5% S% 5%\n18 Un Retail Candy.. 5% 5% 5%\n2 U S LtA Heat pf 1% 1% 1%\n3 Universal Pipe w 1 17% 18% 17%\nMINING.\nCO Arizona Globe Cop .00 .09 .09\n13 Canario Copper 1% 1% 1%\n30 Candelaria Min .05 .05 .05\n5 Con Cop Min new 2\n10 Cork Prov Mines... .07 .07 .07\n81 Cortez Sliver 50 .48 .50\n2 ('reason Gold 3H 3}i 3%\n2 Crown King 1% 1% 1%\n90 Emma Silver 03 .02 .0(1\n660 Fortuna Miuea 13 .11 .12\n20 Goidtleld developm .11 .11 .11\n330 Goldfield Deep Min .12 .11 .12\n8 Goldfield Florence.. .56 .55 .55\n10 Goidtleld Jackpot... .45 .45 .45\n1 Uoliingcr 11 11 11\n70 Marsh Mines 10 .10 .10\n10 McKln Dar 11 .11 .11\n15 Metals Prod 1% 1% 1%\n40 National Tin t .11 .11 .11\n6 New Dominion Cop.. 3 2% 3\n7 N Y Porcupine 50 .50 .50\n70 Nixon Cop 71 .66 .71\n160 Red Hill Florence.. .07 .08 .07\n20 Sandstorm Kendall. .03 .02 .03\n640 Sllverhorn 12 .10 .12\n80 Silver Pick 06 .05 .05\n2 So Am Gold A P... 4 3% 4\n40 Spearhead Gold 10 .09 .09\n60 Stewart Mines 02 .02 .02\n20 Suther Dev Mines.. .41 .40 .41\nI United Verde Ext. 28 28 28\n10 U S Cont new w 1 .10 .19 .19\n1 Unity Gold 3% 3% 3%\n13 Wenden Copper .76 .76 .76\n10 West End Ext .01 .01 .01\n2 Yukon Gold 81 .81 .81\nWashington Stock Exchange.\nSALES.\nWashington Gas ss \u2014sl,ooo at 83%.\nj Washington Gas 6s '33\u201451,000 at 100%.\nWashington Rwy. A Elee. 45\u201452,000 at 71.\nWashington Rwy. Elec. pfd.\u20144 at 71. 7\nat 71. 10 at 71.\nAFTER CALL.\n1 Capital Traction Co.\u2014lo at 100%.\nBONDS.\nBid and Asked Prices.\nPUBLIC UTILITY.\nBid. Asked.\nAmerican Tel. A Teiga. 4\u00bb..... 92 92%\nAmerican Tel. A Teiga. 4%5,102\nI Am. Tel. A Tel, cti. tr. 5s 97% 98\nj Am. Tel. A Tel. conv. 6s 117 118\n1 Anacostia-and Potomac 5s 86 89\nAnacostia and Potomac Guar. ss. 86 89\nC. A P. Tel. 5s 96 97\n0. A P. Telephone of V*. 55..., 92% 94\nCapital Traction R, R. 5s 93% 94%\nCity A Suburban 5a 79%\nGeorgetown Gas Ist 5s 86\nMetropolitan It. H. 5s 97\nPotomac Electric Ist 5s 96\nPotomac Elec. cons. 3g 97\nPotomac Elec. deb. 6s 99%\nPotomac Electric 6s 1953 100% ioi%\nPot. Elec. Pow. g. m. A Kef. 7s. 106 107%\nWash.. Alex. A Mt. Vernon 55.. 28\nWash., Aiex. A Mt. Ver. ctfs.2s\nWash., Balt. A Aunap. 5a 70 72%\nWashington G:is 5s 93 94'\nWashington Gas 6s 100% 101\nWash. Rwy. A Elee. 4s 70% 71%\nWash. Rwy. Elec. g. m. Cs 99%\nMISCELLANEOUS.\nD. C. Paper Mfg. 6s 80\nRiggs Realty 5* (long) 91\nRiggs Realty 5s (slwrt) 97\nSecurity Storage A Safe Dep. 6\u00ab. 95\nWash. Mkt. Cold Storage 3s 94%\nWardman Park Hotel 6a 99\nSTOCKS.\nPUBLIC UTILITY.\nAmerican Tel. A Teiga *123%\nCapital Traction 100% 100%\nWashington Gas *47% 48%\nNorfolk A Wash. Steamboat.... 210 220\nWash. Rwy. A E!ec. com 68% 70\nWash. Rwy. A Elec, pfd 70% 71%\nNATIONAL BANKS.\nCapital 225\nColumbia 225\nCommercial 141 145 1\nDistrict 165 180\nFarmers and Mechanics\u2019 240\nFederal-American 188%\nLiberty 140 145\nLincoln 250\nNational Metropolitan *250\nRiggs *291 390\nSecond 155 161\nNational Bank of Washington... 200 220\nTRUST COMPANY.\nAmerican Security Trust 300 320\nContinental Trust 90 95\nMerchants\u2019 Bank 127% 135\nNational Savings and Trust.... 345\nUnion Trust *l5B 162\nWashington Loan and Trust 345\nSAVINGS BANK.\nCommerce and Savings 200\nI East Washington 18\nSecurity Savings A Commercial.. 275 295\nSeventh Street 175\n[United States 300\nj Washington Mechanics 30\nFIRE INSURANCE.\nAmerican 220\nI Corcoran 120\n{Firemen\u2019s 18\n\u2019National Union.. 9\nTITLE INSURANCE.\nColumbia Title 7\nReal Estate Title 123\nMISCELLANEOUS.\nColumbia Graphophone com\nColumbia Graphophone pfd 2 3\nj I). C. Paper pfd 75\ni Merchants\u2019 Transfer A Storage. 100\nMergenthaier Linotype 139% 160%\ni Old Dutch Market com 1% 4 j\nOld Dutch Market pfd.......... 7\nI Lanston Monotype 73% 74%\nSecurity 5t0rage................. 240\n1 Washington Market 42\nj Yellow Cab 8%\n\u2022Ex dividend.\nBETTER CAR SERVICE.\nBailway Age Notes Marked Change\nIn Bailroad Operation.\nCHICAGO, October 13.\u2014The short\nage of freight cars so noticeable in\nthe peak transportation on the rail\nroads in October, 1922, is not notice\nable this year, according to the Rail\nway Age, a railroad magazine, which\nplaces the credit for this in the more\nefficient handling of cars.\n\u201cThe number of new cars put in\nservice from January 1 to September\n1 was 116,117,\u201d a statement of the\nAge said. \u201cNeverthless, the number\nof freight cars owned by the railways\nIncreased only from 2,307,397 in June,\n1922, to 2,316,255 in June, 1923. This\nIs due to a large number being re\ntired from the service.\u2019\u2019\nFlood of New Security Offerings\nHas Curtailed Buying Power\nHigh Surtaxes Also Keeping Rich People\nFrom Trading in Stock Market.\nBusiness Outlook\nBY STUART P. WEST. I\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star,\ni NEW YORK, October 13. \u2014There are\ntwo reasons for the slackness of buy\ning power which has repeatedly ex\naggerated downward swings on the\nstock exchange. The first is the ab\nsorption of an unusual amount of in\nvestment capital by new security of\nferings. The second is the paralyz\ning effect of high surtaxes upon the\nmarket activities of people of wealth.\nDuring the first half year nearly\n$1,900,000,000 of new stocks and bonds\nwere listed In the New York market,\nan Increase of $320,000,000 over the\nsame period in 1922 and of $620,000,-\n000 over the first half of 1921. Under\nthe urge of competing bankers and\nbanking syndicates local governments\nand private business enterprises\nrushed to sell new securities to a\nthen eager public.\nToo Many New Offerings,\nThe outpour eventually became ex\ncessive. Since the start of the new\n\u2022fiscal year there has been a notice\nable let-up in this new financing. But\nIn the meantime the practical result\nhas been to divert, to an extent far\nbeyond the ordinary, investment\nfunds which normally would have\nbeen attracted by a falling stock\nmarket. As for the wealthy Income\ntaxpayer, his policy is to hold onto\nthe securities he owns, but to be slow\nabout engaging in fresh buying oper\nations In which he must take all the\nrisk and receive only half the profit.\nThe weakening of these two ele\nments of support, although not af\nfecting the final adjustment of mar\nket prices to values, does explain the\ntendency of speculative movements\nto be carried too far temporarily.\nCurrent Business Unusually Large.\nThe opposing views of the business\noutlook remain at the close of the\nweek as they have all along. If com\nparison be made with the feverish\nactivity of last Winter and spring,\nthere has been a considerable reac\ntion in many lines. But if the com\nparison la made with normal situa\ntions the current voulme of produc\ntion and consumption is not only\nsatisfactory, but is unusually large.\nThis, together with the caution\nagainst loading up with surplus goods\nand the unprecedented credit reserve j\nof the country, are the points dwelt j\nupon by those who express confidence\nin the future.\nThose who see things the other way I\nmaintain that production will slump\nas soon as old orders are used up\nand that consumers will continue re-\nluctant to pay the higher prices de- j\nmanded on new contracts. Finally,\nthey maintain that, unable to pass the\nincreased cost of labor and materials i\non to the public, business will have I\nto be content with a slim profit.\nOn this latter point the third quar-\nter earnings statements of the big i\nindustrial companies should throw a\npood deal of light. The s\u2019eel pro- j\nducers were at work all through the I\nperiod on low-priced old contracts,\nwhile paying 15 per cent more in\nwages. Their reports ought to es-\ntabilah just how much there is so\nfar in the argument of the \u201cdwind-\nling profit margin.\u201d\nRailroads Carrying New Business.\nThe contention that the record-\nbreaking railway car loadings are a\nmeasure of business booked six I\nmonths ago, rather than of present I\nactivity, is getting all the time harder\nto substantiate. This might he true\nIf the bulk of the country\u2019s business\nTODAY\n\u2014is the best time to invest in\nFIRST MORTGAGES\nOver a\nQuarter \u2014because your interest at\n\u00b0f a 6 1 2 begins as soon as we re-\nCentury ceive your money.\nWithout\na Loss\n\nB. F. SAUL CO.\nj\nMain 2100 1412 Eye St. N.W.\nINVESTMENT\nRECOMMENDATIONS\nPermit a Word of Counsel Out\nof Our Extensive Experience\nDo not yield to the insidious temptation of promised\nextravagant returns offered by those foisting doubtful\nsecurities upon an unsuspecting public; but invest your\nmoney where the return will be assured at 6y 2 and the\ninterest payable semi-annually on the day due.\nSuch Are Our First Mortgage Notes\nThey are secured by first liens upon income-produc\ning real estate in our beautiful Capital city, which is un\naffected by periods of panics or deflation.\nSince our wist, savants have deciphered the ancient\nrecords, loans secured by first mortgages on real estate\nhave taken FIRST PLACE as safe investments.\nBE AS WISE AS OVR FOREFATHERS\nLet Our Mortgage Department Explain\n{Shannon luch^J\nREALTORS\n713 14th Street N.W.\nMain 2345\ni were taken on long-term contracts,\nbut it Is not. The mass of the mer\nchandise traffic passing over the rail\nroads calls for comparatively quick\npayments and is therefore of recent\norigin. Moreover, according to the\nlatest official .figures, this (lass of\nbusiness is on the increase. If further\ncorroboration is needed. It is afforded\nin the sales of the chain stores, the\nmall order concerns, and other agen\ncies of distribution, which certainly\nshow no let up.\nThe main question, consequently, is\nnot as to the reality of the present\nbusiness but as tc whether It\nIs being conducted at an adequate\nprofit.\n(Copyright, 1923.)\nBAIL HEABINQ DATE SET.\nInvestigation by the Interstate\nCommerce Commission of the feasi\nbility of consolidating railroads into\neighteen or twenty systems will be\nconcluded at hearings here beginning\nNovember 1.\nRepresentatives of all sections of\nthe country, all railroads Involved\nand all communities interested have\nbeen heard, but various points have\nbeen brought up In the testimony\nwhich It is now desired to clear up\nbefore the commission makes a final\nreport. Commissioner Hall, who has\nconducted the hearings to date, will\nbe in charge of the final sessions.\nRATES ON BAB SILVER.\nLONDON, October 13.\u2014Bar silver,\n31 7-16 per ounce.\nMoney. 2% per cent.\nDiscount rates, short bills, 2 15-16a\n3 per cent; three-month bills, 3 3-16\nper cent.\nNEW YORK. October 13.\u2014Bar sil\nver, 63% Mexican dollars, 48%.\nCOMMODITY NEWS\nWIRED STAR FROM\nENTIRE COUNTRY\nDENVER. October 13. Colorado\ncorn growers are smiling with sat\nisfaction with the largest crop ever\nin prospect. The forecast is for 31,-\n000,000 bushels compared with 18,-\n000,000 last year.\nSEATTLE. October 13\u2014Estimates\nshow that there is now in sight\n1 7,243,000 cases of canned Alaska,\ni British Columbia, Puget sound and\nColumbia river salmon, compared\nj with 7,000,000 cases last year.\ni ATLANTA. October 13. \"Roofer\u201d\ni mills, small portable saw mills oper\ni ated by Independent producers, are in\n-1 creasing their output now that much\nof the season\u2019s work on the farms is\nover. These plants turn out framing\nI and sheathing and dispose of their\ni products close at home.\nGARDEN CITY, Kan.. October 13.\nThe sugar beet crop in this section is\nthe best in many years. Estimates for\nKansas, Colorado, Wyoming and Nc\n-1 braska place the 1923 yield 6 per\ncent over last year\u2019s.\nHOUSTON. October 13.\u2014The condl\nj tlon of rice in Texas has dropped to\n85 per cent of norami, as a result of\nI delay in harvesting and threshing and\nj losses due to rains in September. Most\ni of this damage was to early varieties.\nThe yield for the state is estimated\ni at 5.109.000 bushels.\nWEEK SEES WHEAT\nIN NEWUPTURNS\nCorn Also Scores Fine Ad\nvance Due to Scarcity for\nImmediate Delivery.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, October 3 3.\u2014Material\nnew upturns In wheat have occurred\nthis week, largely owing to a reduc\ntion of the government estimate of\nthe domestic spring crop and as a re\nsult of definite steps toward a possible\nincrease of the import duty on wheat.\nCompared with a week ago, wheat\nthis morning ranged from to 2%\nhigher, corn showed 1 Aa1% advance,\noats were to up and provisions\nvaried from 20c decline to 30c gain.\nCorn available for immediate deliv\nery was so scarce that corn and wheat\nbecame virtually equal in value, an\nevent seldom witnessed. Later the\nmarket reflected favorable weather\nfor cutting and husking the new crop.\nOats advanced slightly with other\ngrain.\nFor the most part, provisions were\nlower, affected by weakness of hog\nvalues.\nBUSINESS TOPICS.\nAtlanta Post Office Is Pushed.\nSmoke Retards Shipping.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nATLANTA, October 13.\u2014The In\ncreased volume of mail here has ne\ncessitated taking on forty additional\npost office employes. The city water\nworks department now is rendering\nservice to 280,000 people, 20,000 of whom\nreside outside the corporate limits of\nthis city.\nCHICAGO, October 13. Sales by\nSears. Roebuck Co. are expected to\ntotal approximately $215,000,000 by\nthe end of December. This compares\nwith sales approximating $233,000,000\nin 1919 and 1920.\nDULUTH, October 13 \u2014A heavy\nsmoke pall from forest fires has In\nterfered slightly with lake naviga\ntion. the smoke In certain vessel lanes\nbeing heavier than fog. Trucking by\nmotor in sections near the fire zones\nhas been Bhsndoned.\nFirst Mortgage Loans\nLowest Rates of Interest and Commission.\nPrompt Action\nThomas J. Fisher Company, Inc.\n788 15th Street\nMoney to Loan\n1 \u2014on improved D. C. property\nj at prevailing rates of interest. I\nSee Mr. Field\nHedges Middleton, Inc.\n1334 H ST. N.W.\nFranklin 9503\nFirst Mortgage Loans\nFOR SALE\nIn Convenient Amounts\nat 6*4% interest\nSecured on Improved Properties\nJAMES F. SHEA\n643 Louisiana Ave. N.W.\nMoney to Loan\nANY AMOUNT\nRm.iinablr Charges on\nTrade Acceptance*.\nWarehouse Receipts,\nManufacturer*' Account*,\nShort-Term First and Second\nMortgag