stored.\nThey will be shipped to markets for\nThanksgiving dinners.\nTen cents apiece Is the price for\ngood size pumpkins on many farms.\nCity green grocers are charging from\n15 to 25 cents for pumpkins, with\nhigher prices for unusually large\nones. Town dealers are stocking up\nfor Halloween.\nGrowers say the size of the crop\nshould be a factor In restoring the\n5-cent wedge of pie.\nOver 42,000 Depositors Capital and Surplus, $2,000,000\nMaking Pay Day Deposits\n\u2014BY MAIL suits the\nconvenience of not a few\nof our 42,000 customers,\nand we invite fol-\nIgiHyi i yjlllltllfj service as if you came to\nDeposits Invited in Any Amount; Same Rate of\nInterest Paid on Small and Large Accounts\ni\nOpen Until 5:30 PM Monday and Tuesday\nOFFICERS: DIRECTORS:\nWILLIAM D nOOVEB President Woodbury Blair William D. Hoover\nWOODBURY BLAIR lat V. Free. Jamca A. Buchanan Reginald S. Huidekoper\nFRANK W. STONE ....2d V. Prea. William A. H. Church Victor Kauffmans\nFRANK STETSON Truet Officer Walter C. Clephane Charles Minsball\nCUAS. C. LAiIBUHN Treasurer U. Rosier Dulany, Jr. Edmund D. Rheeta\nB PERCIVAL WlLSON....Secretary Wm. E. Edmonaton Frank Stetson\nF. K. ULLMER. Aast. Sec. ft Aast. Tr. Franklin H. Ellis Frank W. Stone\nBRPCE BAIRD ..Asst. Trust Officer Frederick A. Fenntn* William H. Walker\nDAVID BOBNET. .Asst. Tru.t Officer H. Prescott Galley Henry K. Willard\nNational Savings Trust Co.\n56th Oldest Savings Depository in Washington\nYear Cor. 15th and New York Ave.\n\nIn the Path of\nWashington's Growth\nQUR First Mortgages owe their dou\nv ble security to the impregnable\nsafety of Washington and our choice of\nvaluable, improved property in the path\nof the city\u2019s growth.\nEvery loan secured by our First Mort\ngage Notes holds a fifty to one hundred\nper cent margin of safety in the value\nof the property, and is arranged in short\nterms to permit periodical investigation.\nThese Notes are available in denomi\nnations of SIOO to SIOO,OOO, and may be\npurch